irca 1093","1120":"1120","1163":"1163","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1179":"1179","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","aft 1130":"na 1130","1199":"1199","about 7 December 1130":"circa 7 december 1130","from 1097 to 1199":"van 1097 to 1199","about 1135":"circa 1135","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"abt 1093–1179":"about 1093–1179","1093–1179":"1093–1179","1120–1163":"1120–1163","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1135–Male":"1135–Deceased","1138–Male":"1138–Deceased","1090–1130":"1090–1130","1070–1199":"1070–1199","1090":"1090","abt 1093":"about 1093","1120":"1120","1163":"1163","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1179":"1179","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","aft 1130":"after 1130","1199":"1199","about 7 December 1130":"about 7 December 1130","from 1097 to 1199":"from 1097 to 1199","about 1135":"about 1135","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Workington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): habitational name from Wormington in Gloucestershire or Berry Wormington in Stanton (also Gloucestershire). Perhaps also from Warmington in Northamptonshire. The placenames derive from an Old English personal name <i>Wyrma</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"High","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","nickname for a tall man, from Middle English <i>heigh</i>, <i>hey</i>, <i>high</i> ‘high, tall’ (Old English <i>hēah</i>). Compare   Hay   3.","topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) height or hill’, from Middle English <i>heigh</i> ‘height, hilltop’ (Old English <i>hēah</i>). Compare   Hight  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hay","meanings":["Scottish and English (northern; of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy called <i>La Haie</i> or <i>La Haye</i> (Old French <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, enclosure’, ‘forest for hunting deer and other animals’, a borrowing of the ancient Germanic word <i>haga</i>). Robert <i>de Haia</i> or <i>de la Haye</i> is known to have come from La Haye-du-Puits in Manche; he was the founder of Boxgrove Priory in Sussex (1123), and holder of the Honor of Halnaker (Sussex) and (by marriage) the barony of Kolswein (Lincolnshire). The Norman name was also taken to Ireland, where it has since flourished in the county of Wexford as <i>Hay</i> and   Hayes  . Elsewhere in Ireland the name usually has a native Irish origin, see below.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>hay(e)</i>, <i>heye</i>, <i>heghe</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>(ge)hæg</i>) or ‘forest fenced off for hunting’ (Old French <i>haie</i>); or else a habitational name from a place so called, such as Hay (in Herefordshire and Westmorland) or Hey in Scammonden (Yorkshire). It was no doubt sometimes synonymous with   Hayward  .","English: nickname for a tall man, from Middle English <i>heigh</i>, <i>hey</i>, <i>high</i> ‘high, tall’ (Old English <i>hēah</i>)."]},{"name":"Hy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heng, Hong, Sang, Dong, Khin, Kin, Kong, Man, Sin, Yong.  Vietnamese Soi, Cong, Dang, Dau, Duoc, Mui, Nhi, Phu, Quyen, Tau.","English: variant of   High  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 解, based on its pronunciation in Taishanese, a variant of Cantonese, see   Xie   2."]}]},{"name":"Ireby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Irby in Lincolnshire, Cheshire, and North Yorkshire, or Ireby (Cumberland and Lancashire), all named from Old Norse <i>Írabýr</i> ‘settlement of the Irish’. Compare   Ireton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ireton","meanings":["English: most probably a habitational name from Kirk Ireton (Derbyshire) or perhaps from Ireton Farm in Weston Underwood (Derbyshire), both named in Anglo-Scandinavian as <i>Íratūn</i> ‘settlement of the Irish’ or more likely ‘settlement of the Irishman’. The reference may be either to a Scandinavian Viking who had been in Ireland or to an Irishman who came to England with the Vikings. Occasionally the name may also derive from either of two places called Irton in North Yorkshire, of which Irton in Seamer parish is a more likely source than the lost Irton in Coxwold. Both the North Yorkshire places have the same etymologies as those above."]},{"name":"Erby","meanings":["English: variant of   Irby  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Gospatric","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Another orthography of Cospatrick."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":3,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":13,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Gospatric de Workington of High Ireby was born about 1093, his father, Orme De Workington Baron of Kendal, was 5 and his mother, Gunnilda of Dunbar, was 25. He had at least 3 sons with Egeline d'Engaine. He died in 1179, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, at the age of 87."},"et":{"abt 1093–1179":"umbes 1093–1179","109